WEBVTT

00:29.378 --> 00:30.219
Good morning, Northridge.

00:30.239 --> 00:30.940
How are you guys?

00:31.982 --> 00:32.803
Good to see you.

00:32.843 --> 00:36.889
My name is Pete, I'm one of the pastors here at Northridge.

00:36.909 --> 00:39.733
We're honored to hear when I welcome those of you that are online as well.

00:39.753 --> 00:40.755
We're so glad you're with us.

00:40.795 --> 00:41.876
Wouldn't worship great today.

00:42.577 --> 00:51.150
It's always nice sometimes just to kind of bring it down a little bit slower and it really fits in with the whole theme of what we're talking about today, which is rest.

00:51.751 --> 00:56.658
The only difficult part of that worship was a part where Evan tried to get us to clap and sing at the same time.

00:58.274 --> 01:00.919
Like, I always, I'm like, okay, I got it this time.

01:00.939 --> 01:01.560
I'm gonna do it.

01:01.700 --> 01:08.752
And like five seconds into it, as soon as I try to sing and clap, it's like my brain's like, bro, you gotta choose one or the other.

01:09.514 --> 01:11.517
We can't do both, so I just chose to sing.

01:11.918 --> 01:14.923
And it's always fun to watch on each service.

01:14.943 --> 01:17.427
You guys, by the way, you made it longer than the other services.

01:17.748 --> 01:20.312
You were like 20 seconds strong of clapping.

01:20.613 --> 01:23.538
And then all of you guys were kind of like, yeah, I can't do it either.

01:23.778 --> 01:25.680
Yeah, I'm just going to stick to singing.

01:25.760 --> 01:26.241
It's fun.

01:26.281 --> 01:26.641
I love it.

01:26.982 --> 01:31.006
So we're talking about rest today, because we've been in this series called What If It's True.

01:31.246 --> 01:37.213
And one of the things we're going to talk about today is what if it's true that the Sabbath was taken seriously by God?

01:37.654 --> 01:46.624
What if it's true that the Sabbath was actually a gift intended like to give us life, not to take life away?

01:46.704 --> 01:52.370
What if it's true that you were designed to live with a certain rhythm in your life?

01:52.802 --> 02:00.491
And if you can grasp on to what it is we're going to talk about today, I promise you, it can change the way that you work.

02:00.511 --> 02:08.319
So we're going to talk about rest, but let me talk about work for just a second because there's a balance to these two things as we're going to see as we talk about rest today.

02:08.880 --> 02:15.587
And what I want you to understand as we talk about rest is first and foremost, God actually does care about your work.

02:15.607 --> 02:16.849
He cares about your work.

02:16.869 --> 02:18.130
He cares about what you do.

02:18.402 --> 02:20.926
He cares about the company that you work for or that you lead.

02:21.226 --> 02:23.049
He cares about the customers that you serve.

02:23.109 --> 02:26.414
He cares about the gifts and the abilities that he's given you to do this work.

02:26.715 --> 02:30.881
He cares about the families that we lead and we manage as work, right?

02:30.901 --> 02:33.025
He cares about what we do.

02:33.706 --> 02:44.242
And I don't think, I always want to make sure I point this out, I don't believe that there are like secular jobs and sacred jobs.

02:44.642 --> 02:44.862
Right?

02:44.922 --> 02:47.386
And some people, that's the way you kind of view life.

02:47.406 --> 02:49.209
Like there's these sacred jobs over here.

02:49.589 --> 02:56.881
These are the jobs like really matter to God, like pastors and missionaries and social workers and people like that, right?

02:56.901 --> 02:58.383
Those are these sacred jobs.

02:58.663 --> 03:04.692
And then there's these secular jobs over here that the vast majority of us are doing that maybe don't count quite as much.

03:04.973 --> 03:06.134
But listen, you have to understand this.

03:06.335 --> 03:11.122
You don't get more points for being a missionary over a hairstylist.

03:11.234 --> 03:16.283
or you don't get more points for being a pastor than you do being a CEO, right?

03:16.303 --> 03:18.787
There's no sacred, it's all sacred.

03:19.328 --> 03:20.891
Everything that you do matters.

03:21.352 --> 03:24.217
What you do matters and the way in which you do it matters.

03:24.538 --> 03:27.102
And scripture talks a lot about this from the very beginning.

03:27.483 --> 03:31.410
Before the fall, before sin, God had given Adam

03:31.554 --> 03:35.539
a job, he'd get him responsibility, he'd given him purpose.

03:35.899 --> 03:42.007
So your gifts, your abilities, the work you do, the way you do it, all that matters.

03:42.287 --> 03:43.529
It really does count.

03:44.270 --> 03:50.918
But it's also possible to take something that was given to us as a gift, right?

03:50.938 --> 03:58.728
That was given to us in a way in which it was supposed to serve us, but if not looked at and treated properly, it actually begins to enslave you.

03:59.629 --> 04:00.370
It's possible.

04:00.610 --> 04:03.674
If you think about it in your life, there's multiple things, right?

04:04.015 --> 04:13.809
That God has given to you as a gift, and it's meant to serve you, but if it's taken out of the proper context, it actually begins to enslave you.

04:14.310 --> 04:19.537
And one of those things can be work, can be your gifts and your abilities.

04:20.078 --> 04:25.906
And I think that the vast majority of people living in our culture today are missing something.

04:26.306 --> 04:33.475
And the vast majority of you listening to this message, whether you're here in this room or you're watching online, I believe the vast majority of are missing something.

04:34.176 --> 04:38.742
And we're missing something and our culture is okay with you missing this something.

04:39.282 --> 04:44.349
In fact, our culture sometimes celebrates people who are missing this something.

04:44.910 --> 04:51.598
People in our culture can get promoted for intentionally dodging this thing that many of us are missing.

04:51.899 --> 04:54.642
And for lack of a better term, the thing that we're missing

04:55.362 --> 04:56.403
is breathing room.

04:57.765 --> 04:58.926
It's a little bit of breathing room.

04:59.607 --> 05:07.034
If you find yourself kind of going through life and going through all the motions and inside, you're just thinking to yourself, I just need a little breathing room.

05:07.515 --> 05:08.676
I need a little space.

05:09.137 --> 05:13.501
I need this whole thing called life to slow down just a little bit.

05:13.882 --> 05:21.650
We have a culture that chronically overworks and has taken it to the point where we've actually made overwork and busyness a value

05:22.050 --> 05:23.893
Like, that is a good thing.

05:24.233 --> 05:38.895
But the reality is, if we know this, like we get really honest about this conversation, all the studies out there, all the research, all the collective wisdom points to the fact that living an overworked, busy, frenzied lifestyle is not good for you.

05:38.915 --> 05:40.938
It's not good for your families.

05:42.220 --> 05:49.852
And yet, I bet a bunch of you who are caught up in that pattern of overworking busyness, if you and I were to go to lunch today and I would just say, hey, let's figure this thing out.

05:49.912 --> 05:51.474
Why are you doing this to yourself?

05:51.938 --> 05:53.840
You might say something like this to me.

05:54.741 --> 05:57.163
I'm doing it for my family, right?

05:57.183 --> 05:59.646
I want my kids to have some opportunities that I didn't have.

06:00.106 --> 06:04.470
And if I had you hooked up to a lie detector test, you'd pass it.

06:05.231 --> 06:06.252
You really believe that.

06:07.253 --> 06:18.144
But you know how many people I know who have used that excuse for decades, only the one day wake up and this family that they thought they were doing all this for are gone.

06:18.164 --> 06:20.146
They're gone.

06:20.866 --> 06:22.128
because they never got loved.

06:22.429 --> 06:24.853
They never felt seen, right?

06:25.615 --> 06:27.278
And they were just doing life without you.

06:27.959 --> 06:31.285
There's a lot of different reasons we do this, but we know it's not good for our families.

06:31.485 --> 06:32.708
We know it's not good for our health.

06:32.988 --> 06:34.591
All the studies out there, right?

06:34.772 --> 06:44.850
The whole health care industry believes and agrees that so many of our common ailments from heart disease to cancer are directly related to overwork and busyness.

06:45.218 --> 06:58.255
CNN study that was recently done showed that people who worked an 11-hour day were 250% more likely to get depression than somebody who works an eight-hour day.

06:58.976 --> 07:04.523
It impacts us physically, it impacts us mentally, and there are a lot of reasons why we do this, right?

07:04.643 --> 07:10.050
Even though it's not good for us, there are a lot of reasons why we do this, and that's why it's kind of hard to solve this whole problem.

07:10.430 --> 07:13.394
For some of you, overwork and business is

07:13.570 --> 07:15.612
directly tied to your identity.

07:16.433 --> 07:17.274
That's why you do this.

07:17.894 --> 07:21.718
You wouldn't know who you are without the overwork and the busyness.

07:21.778 --> 07:23.119
It's become a part of your identity.

07:23.480 --> 07:27.163
And you think that your worth is tied directly to what it is that you do.

07:27.243 --> 07:31.908
You don't know who you would be without your work, without your gifts, without your abilities.

07:32.208 --> 07:37.453
And so you just keep driving forward like thinking that's how you're gonna make yourself somebody.

07:38.174 --> 07:42.578
Some of us are driven to overwork and busyness because we're just people pleasers.

07:42.818 --> 07:44.408
like some of us are just wired that way.

07:44.448 --> 07:48.434
Any kind of type A people here like me are just kind of wired that way.

07:48.930 --> 07:50.652
oldest in the family, right?

07:50.792 --> 07:51.733
Oldest of the siblings.

07:51.993 --> 07:57.098
We just have this thing inside of us where we feel like we want to take responsibility for everybody.

07:57.118 --> 07:59.220
We want to take responsibility for everything.

07:59.581 --> 08:03.885
We're the kind of people that are wired that if you get an email, you got to respond to immediately.

08:03.945 --> 08:07.149
If you get a phone call, you got to call that person right back.

08:07.569 --> 08:09.451
You know, it's like you're tied to your phone 24-7.

08:09.471 --> 08:12.013
Say, I have my phone on me now.

08:12.274 --> 08:13.555
Why do I have my phone on me now?

08:14.176 --> 08:16.498
Am I going to answer a phone call in the next 30 minutes?

08:16.994 --> 08:18.476
or respond to a text?

08:18.596 --> 08:20.298
No, there's nothing I can even do with this.

08:20.358 --> 08:22.381
Like, why do I feel like I have to have it on me?

08:22.401 --> 08:23.502
But we feel that way, right?

08:24.003 --> 08:24.824
I've seen some of you.

08:24.864 --> 08:27.528
I've seen some of you already send two or three texts.

08:28.990 --> 08:30.371
The first five minutes of this mess.

08:30.431 --> 08:32.434
You guys know I can see you, right?

08:34.256 --> 08:35.718
There is not a wall here.

08:35.738 --> 08:36.499
I can see.

08:37.060 --> 08:38.282
Last week, this is funny.

08:38.302 --> 08:39.303
I think it was right where you're sitting.

08:39.323 --> 08:39.884
It wasn't you, though.

08:39.924 --> 08:40.805
I want to make that clear.

08:41.506 --> 08:44.690
Dude was knocked out cold two minutes into the message.

08:45.026 --> 08:46.789
Totally out like I'm watching me.

08:46.809 --> 09:01.252
It's not it's not like he's trying to fight it You know how we sometimes we fight it and sure he what he gave up the fight He was out cool, and he had a cup of coffee right there in the thing and I'm like somebody opened his mouth and just poured in there It's not doing them any good sitting there in the cup holder.

09:01.332 --> 09:03.075
He needs some caffeine, right?

09:03.375 --> 09:07.061
So maybe here's a new rule because it's totally cool if you need to take an app during the message, right?

09:08.263 --> 09:10.226
Let's at least sit five rows back

09:11.490 --> 09:17.098
Let's reserve the first five rows for those of you who would like to choose to stay awake throughout the course of this message.

09:17.338 --> 09:18.880
If you're up in a balcony, you can lay down.

09:18.920 --> 09:20.502
I can't see squat up there.

09:21.904 --> 09:24.527
You can lay down, have a good time, play checkers, whatever.

09:24.648 --> 09:26.430
I cannot see a thing up there.

09:26.470 --> 09:26.991
You're safe.

09:27.211 --> 09:29.454
But you guys, I need you to engage a little bit.

09:29.474 --> 09:30.375
Just keep your eyes open.

09:30.435 --> 09:31.116
That would be great.

09:31.156 --> 09:32.458
It'd be awesome.

09:32.478 --> 09:33.660
What are we even talking about?

09:33.680 --> 09:34.861
I am so lost.

09:39.127 --> 09:41.330
That was about overworked, Sabbath.

09:42.210 --> 09:48.419
God, Jesus, it's like, we have a lot of excuses, right, for why we fall on this pattern.

09:49.220 --> 09:55.149
And so for some of you, again, you're using excuse that it's just a season, but you've been saying that now, right, for decades.

09:55.169 --> 09:57.152
For some of you, you're like, oh, it's just my industry.

09:57.492 --> 09:58.334
I don't have a choice.

09:58.834 --> 10:04.543
So maybe you're gonna say it's the number of kids you have, or the age that they are, or that you just lack discipline in your life.

10:04.603 --> 10:06.706
Listen, all these excuses

10:06.786 --> 10:15.598
could be contributing factors, but let me tell you the number one reason why we overwork and live these busy, frenzied lifestyle.

10:15.998 --> 10:18.922
The number one reason I believe is fear.

10:21.045 --> 10:23.869
You fear that you're gonna get behind, right?

10:24.250 --> 10:28.976
And so if you don't work at 80 hour a week, somebody else might work at 80 hour a week and they might get ahead of you.

10:29.637 --> 10:36.306
If your kid's not enlisted in soccer, lacrosse, baseball, basketball, chorus,

10:36.514 --> 10:38.816
Scouts are all at the same time.

10:38.856 --> 10:43.401
Your kids might be slipping behind, right?

10:43.421 --> 10:46.504
We fear that somehow we're getting behind.

10:46.544 --> 10:50.047
We fear that we're missing out or we fear that our kids are missing out.

10:50.327 --> 10:52.569
We fear that we might miss out on a little bit of money.

10:52.890 --> 10:54.832
We might miss out on a little bit of opportunity.

10:55.072 --> 10:56.493
We might miss out on that title.

10:56.773 --> 10:59.076
We might miss out on that corner office.

10:59.596 --> 11:01.638
We fear falling behind.

11:02.139 --> 11:05.682
Bottom line is the core fear that so many of us have

11:05.762 --> 11:07.544
We fear not mattering.

11:09.026 --> 11:10.368
We fear that our lives won't matter.

11:11.230 --> 11:19.761
And what's crazy, this is so ironic, our fear of not mattering is keeping a lot of us from what actually matters the most.

11:20.823 --> 11:24.227
And from the very beginning of time, God established a rhythm.

11:24.308 --> 11:29.254
He literally baked this into creation, the way in which He created our world.

11:29.535 --> 11:30.696
He baked this into the rhythm.

11:30.756 --> 11:31.678
He wanted to show us.

11:31.738 --> 11:32.719
He wanted to model this.

11:33.140 --> 11:34.802
He was never His intention.

11:35.458 --> 11:41.610
that we would get our identity, that we would get our worth, that we would get our value from work and from business.

11:41.690 --> 11:42.391
It was important.

11:42.431 --> 11:49.645
He wanted us to have purpose, but all along he had this plan for breathing room, and it was called the Sabbath.

11:49.985 --> 11:55.195
So just to make sure we're on the same page, it's just a generic definition of what the Sabbath is.

11:55.235 --> 11:58.802
It's just breaking from our regular, frenzied activities.

11:59.170 --> 12:08.085
to participate in activities that refresh, remind, and encourage our understanding that we are loved and cherished by a good God.

12:09.327 --> 12:11.331
That's all it is, very basic, right?

12:11.611 --> 12:13.554
Don't wanna over-complicate this thing.

12:13.895 --> 12:15.478
All it is is a break.

12:15.998 --> 12:25.234
It's a disruption in the normal pattern so that we can stop, we can slow down, maybe even pause, right, and engage in activities

12:25.410 --> 12:30.197
Whenever those activities might be, and we'll talk a little bit more about that in a minute, it's gonna be different for all of us, right?

12:30.598 --> 12:38.449
There are things that are gonna help us refresh, remind, and encourage our understanding that we are loved and that we are cherished by a good God.

12:38.670 --> 12:41.374
This has been God's plan from the very beginning.

12:41.955 --> 12:47.543
Now, I wanna be real careful, but let's talk about how this happens, and the bottom line is, you have to choose it.

12:48.284 --> 12:49.486
You have to choose the Sabbath.

12:49.806 --> 12:51.990
The Sabbath is not something that just happens to you.

12:52.370 --> 12:54.994
You have to make a conscious decision that you wanna choose it.

12:55.266 --> 13:04.961
Now, I want to be real careful here in how I kind of coach us to how we apply the Sabbath to our life, because in the time of Jesus, they had really manipulated the Sabbath.

13:05.682 --> 13:17.901
The Pharisees, the religious leaders in their legalism took something that was intended to be a gift, the Sabbath, intended to be about refreshment, about renewal, about connecting to God's love and God's grace.

13:18.161 --> 13:22.387
It's about reminding us that we're not just human doings, we're actually human beings.

13:22.788 --> 13:24.050
They took that gift.

13:24.194 --> 13:25.276
And they manipulated it.

13:25.796 --> 13:33.828
And they created dozens and dozens and dozens of laws about what you could do, what you couldn't do, when it started, when it stopped.

13:33.848 --> 13:35.650
And they ruined the gift.

13:35.971 --> 13:38.594
So I want to be real careful not to get legalistic about this.

13:38.915 --> 13:42.460
But one of the things that I know about this Sabbath is you have to choose it.

13:42.740 --> 13:44.042
It's not just going to happen to you.

13:44.603 --> 13:45.865
Nobody can do this for you.

13:46.225 --> 13:47.647
Your spouse can't choose it for you.

13:47.667 --> 13:49.229
Your kids can't choose it for you.

13:49.610 --> 13:50.972
Parents can't choose it for you.

13:50.992 --> 13:52.434
You have to make this decision.

13:52.866 --> 14:00.073
And the Sabbath is all about helping us worship a good God and not the good work that he's given us.

14:00.894 --> 14:05.718
But the tricky thing about the Sabbath is that it's a form of rest, right?

14:05.738 --> 14:07.820
But it's different than sleep.

14:07.840 --> 14:09.282
Sleep can be forced on you.

14:10.062 --> 14:14.647
If you go long enough without sleep, your body will completely shut down.

14:14.947 --> 14:15.868
You will pass out.

14:16.188 --> 14:17.930
Sleep will force itself on you.

14:18.290 --> 14:20.352
Sabbath doesn't do that, right?

14:21.273 --> 14:22.194
The Sabbath

14:22.274 --> 14:25.158
If you resist it, it pulls back.

14:26.220 --> 14:28.343
The Sabbath is easy to skirt.

14:28.684 --> 14:40.402
In fact, it's easy to go your entire life skirting the Sabbath, not taking advantage of the Sabbath, and never figure out that that was part of the reason that you were in so much pain.

14:41.570 --> 14:55.445
To never figure out that it's part of the reason that your work was actually so unsatisfying and your friendships were so fragile and your family was so splintered and you just felt so frenzied.

14:56.206 --> 15:03.414
It's easy to skip the Sabbath and not connect the dots to how it's impacting your life and your work and your family.

15:03.875 --> 15:05.296
So nobody can do this for you.

15:06.478 --> 15:08.039
And the big question is why?

15:08.060 --> 15:10.322
Why were we designed like this?

15:10.402 --> 15:11.964
What is the whole purpose of the Sabbath?

15:11.984 --> 15:13.065
And I'm gonna give you two things.

15:13.145 --> 15:17.550
The first thing that the Sabbath does for us is it just reminds us of our limitations.

15:18.251 --> 15:21.595
And we'll look at two separate texts and talk about the Sabbath.

15:22.055 --> 15:23.577
They sound very similar by the way.

15:23.617 --> 15:28.002
The first one's in Exodus and we'll look at another one here in just a second that's out of the book of Deuteronomy.

15:28.503 --> 15:38.514
And they sound very similar except for what the author does is ties the event or the commandment of the Sabbath to two separate events.

15:38.690 --> 15:45.003
The first event you're going to see in Exodus is he ties it to creation, so that you can be reminded of your limitation.

15:45.023 --> 15:49.232
So Exodus 20 says, remember to observe the Sabbath day by keeping it holy.

15:50.194 --> 15:55.906
You have six days each week for your ordinary work, but the seventh day is a Sabbath day.

15:56.246 --> 15:57.970
So he's showing us a rhythm.

15:58.082 --> 16:01.048
It's a day of rest dedicated to the Lord your God.

16:01.088 --> 16:03.232
On that day, no one in your household may do any work.

16:03.252 --> 16:08.822
This includes you, your sons, your daughters, your male and female servants, your livestock and any foreigners living among you.

16:09.163 --> 16:15.755
For in the six days that the Lord made the heavens, the earth and the sea and everything in them, but on the seventh day he rested.

16:15.795 --> 16:19.282
That is why the Lord blessed the Sabbath day and he set it apart as holy.

16:19.554 --> 16:22.218
So he takes this out and then he talks about, hey, this is a special day.

16:22.458 --> 16:23.259
It's a unique day.

16:23.500 --> 16:25.142
It's not supposed to be like the other days.

16:25.522 --> 16:32.052
And one of the reasons you're gonna do that is it's gonna remind you that that was the exact same pattern in which God created the world, right?

16:32.212 --> 16:33.594
We've been made in his image.

16:33.854 --> 16:36.538
So that means we work in a similar pattern that he works.

16:36.838 --> 16:41.545
And God modeled for us this pattern of work, work, work, work, work, rest.

16:43.347 --> 16:45.851
Work, work, work, work, work, rest.

16:46.792 --> 16:48.114
And if God needed that,

16:48.610 --> 16:51.234
How much more do you and I need that?

16:52.155 --> 16:57.322
So the observance of the Sabbath is tied directly to creation.

16:57.882 --> 16:59.164
So rhythm of work is key.

16:59.184 --> 16:59.845
There's a pattern.

16:59.865 --> 17:00.526
There's a groove.

17:00.967 --> 17:06.174
Overwork and underwork both violate our very nature of how we've been created.

17:06.955 --> 17:11.401
Understand that there's a balance between work and rest.

17:11.961 --> 17:12.402
Work.

17:12.482 --> 17:20.978
And rest, it's this pattern, God's saying, I want you to imitate me in order to discover that you're not me and that deep down inside you truly need me.

17:21.700 --> 17:23.764
And there's something about this rest, right?

17:23.844 --> 17:30.637
We see it in other places in Scripture Psalms 46, is be still and know that I am God, right?

17:30.757 --> 17:31.278
Be still.

17:31.358 --> 17:35.506
Like, what is it about being still that makes it easier to know that he's God?

17:35.618 --> 17:36.619
Well, that's pretty easy, right?

17:36.920 --> 17:49.276
When you're busy and you're frenzied and you're always running around manipulating, controlling things, everything in your life, it's really easy to begin to convince yourself that you're like God, that you're in control, that if you don't do it, it won't happen.

17:49.857 --> 17:50.878
Very easy to get caught.

17:50.898 --> 18:01.212
So he says, every once in a while, you need to be still, because when you get still, you come into that knowledge and that realization that there is a God and it's not me, right?

18:01.413 --> 18:05.458
See, we don't practice the Sabbath because all the work got done.

18:06.338 --> 18:13.767
No, we practice the Sabbath because God promises us that He'll make up for the work that we didn't get done, right?

18:13.827 --> 18:24.441
And if God can take any messes and mishaps and wreckage and choreographed beauty and meaning from it, then I think you can take a day off.

18:25.902 --> 18:28.866
Now, if He can't, you better get busy, right?

18:30.148 --> 18:35.314
He's either, God's either good and in control

18:36.482 --> 18:39.005
Or you better try a lot harder, right?

18:39.046 --> 18:40.227
It's kind of that simple.

18:40.588 --> 18:43.952
And so part of the Sabbath, it's reminding us of our limitation.

18:44.173 --> 18:49.139
The second thing that the Sabbath reminds us of is God's care and God's plan, right?

18:49.159 --> 18:49.820
That's what it does.

18:49.900 --> 18:52.184
Here's the other passage I was telling you about, Deuteronomy 5.

18:52.204 --> 18:56.710
It says, observe the Sabbath day by keeping it holy as a Lord your God has commanded you.

18:56.750 --> 18:59.794
You have six days each week for your ordinary work.

19:00.226 --> 19:03.850
But the seventh day is the Sabbath day of rest dedicated to the Lord your God.

19:03.890 --> 19:06.613
On that day, no one in your household may do any work.

19:06.633 --> 19:12.560
This includes you, your sons, your daughters, your male and female servant, your oxen, your donkey, all your livestock, and any foreigners living among you.

19:13.141 --> 19:15.624
All your male and female servants must rest as you do.

19:15.964 --> 19:19.027
Remember, now here's where it switches up, right?

19:19.048 --> 19:24.754
It sounded exactly like that Exodus passage, but the Exodus passage tied the Sabbath

19:24.866 --> 19:33.254
to the pattern of creation, now what's gonna happen here is he's gonna tie it to a very significant event in the nation of Israel's history.

19:33.274 --> 19:41.241
He says, remember that you were once slaves in Egypt, but the Lord your God brought you out with this strong hand of power for our arm.

19:41.261 --> 19:45.225
That is why the Lord your God has commanded you to rest on the Sabbath day.

19:45.806 --> 19:47.607
So now he's gonna tie it to their history.

19:48.288 --> 19:52.932
So see what happened is he's saying, hey, listen, there was a day that you guys were slaves.

19:53.573 --> 19:54.834
That was your story.

19:55.202 --> 19:58.566
For 400 years, you guys were slaves in Egypt.

19:58.826 --> 20:03.231
And what that looked like for them, a typical day, was just work, right?

20:03.271 --> 20:04.712
They made bricks for Pharaoh.

20:05.093 --> 20:07.636
So it was bricks, bricks, bricks, bricks, bricks.

20:08.156 --> 20:10.779
Late at night, they got a little bit to eat, if they were lucky.

20:11.500 --> 20:21.991
Then they got a little bit of rest, and they woke up the next day, and it was bricks, bricks, bricks, bricks, bricks, bricks into the day, a little bit of food, a little bit of rest, and right back.

20:22.172 --> 20:24.434
Seven days a week for four

20:24.514 --> 20:27.819
100 years, that was their pattern of life.

20:28.500 --> 20:30.302
They were not treated like human beings.

20:30.322 --> 20:31.945
They were treated like human doings.

20:32.506 --> 20:35.630
All of their value was in making bricks.

20:36.532 --> 20:43.542
And so now God kind of intervenes and brings Moses into the picture and leads them out of 400 years of slavery.

20:44.103 --> 20:45.384
So now they've been set free.

20:45.445 --> 20:50.011
But just because you've been set free doesn't mean that you know how to live free.

20:50.051 --> 20:51.033
Right?

20:51.053 --> 20:51.954
There's a difference.

20:52.194 --> 20:59.783
So they've been technically set free, but 400 years of slavery, 400 years of thinking your only value came from making bricks, right?

21:00.083 --> 21:04.248
Now you've got to learn what it means to actually be free, to actually live free.

21:04.709 --> 21:08.874
So God and his loving kindness and wisdom said, I'm going to help you guys out.

21:09.114 --> 21:11.737
We're going to start this new community called the Nation of Israel.

21:12.177 --> 21:12.898
You're my people.

21:13.459 --> 21:16.082
And we're going to do things a little differently in this community.

21:16.226 --> 21:22.393
And I got to teach you guys what it means, what it looks like to live free in community with one another.

21:22.813 --> 21:24.195
And then it gives them the Ten Commandments.

21:24.615 --> 21:25.837
That's all the Ten Commandments were.

21:26.798 --> 21:32.824
It was like, I'm going to give you kind of a model for what it's like to be free and live in community with one another.

21:32.845 --> 21:35.407
It was like, I'm going to give you some things that are going to really help you out.

21:35.568 --> 21:36.428
Like, try this.

21:37.069 --> 21:41.394
Let your stuff just be your stuff and don't steal your neighbor's stuff.

21:42.114 --> 21:46.780
If you'll do that, if you'll not take his stuff, don't steal his donkey, guess what?

21:47.121 --> 21:49.384
This community thing is gonna work out a lot better.

21:49.785 --> 21:50.626
So just do that.

21:51.347 --> 21:52.448
He's like, I'll give you another tip.

21:52.588 --> 21:58.436
How about your wife just stays your wife and your neighbor's wife just stays his wife?

21:59.278 --> 21:59.758
How about that?

22:00.559 --> 22:04.064
Just let his wife be his wife and your wife be your wife and guess what?

22:04.585 --> 22:06.467
This community thing is gonna work out a lot better.

22:07.048 --> 22:08.570
Life's gonna be a lot easier for you.

22:09.211 --> 22:11.314
And then one of the other Ten Commandments he gave him

22:11.458 --> 22:12.379
was the Sabbath day.

22:12.940 --> 22:16.804
He's like, listen, I'm gonna teach you guys what it's like to be human, right?

22:17.165 --> 22:18.446
And here's the reality.

22:18.806 --> 22:24.513
I did not create you just to work, work, work, work, work, work, work, work, work, work, work, work, work, work, work.

22:24.533 --> 22:25.574
No, there's a pattern.

22:25.774 --> 22:26.916
There's a rhythm to this.

22:27.316 --> 22:29.419
You are more than what you do.

22:29.859 --> 22:35.466
And on the Sabbath day, I'm gonna help you remember that you're a human being, not a human doing.

22:36.287 --> 22:39.250
See, they thought they didn't have the right to rest.

22:40.450 --> 22:42.713
And that's exactly what some of you have been convinced of.

22:42.733 --> 22:45.296
You don't think you have the right to rest.

22:46.317 --> 22:48.059
And technically, that might be true, right?

22:48.100 --> 22:51.023
There's a lot of things in my life I don't absolutely have the right to.

22:51.103 --> 22:52.625
I don't have the right to my home.

22:52.665 --> 22:54.147
I don't have the right to my family.

22:54.427 --> 22:55.949
I don't have the right to my job.

22:56.250 --> 22:57.912
I don't have the right to my salvation.

22:58.252 --> 23:03.899
So yes, we could add rest to that list and say, yeah, I don't have the right for that.

23:04.800 --> 23:09.426
But thank God, my God, could care less about my rights.

23:10.018 --> 23:13.803
And what he cares about and what he cares about deeply are my needs.

23:14.684 --> 23:22.834
And he's created me in such a way where I have the undeniable need for rest in my life.

23:24.036 --> 23:28.521
And the Sabbath is just about God saying, listen, your ultimate responsibility is not to take care of yourself.

23:28.902 --> 23:30.564
That's my ultimate responsibility.

23:31.145 --> 23:35.250
Now, the truth is, God has set up an economy in our world

23:35.874 --> 23:40.385
where for the most part we do meet our means through natural ways, right?

23:40.986 --> 23:43.211
Scripture says, six days you'll work.

23:43.231 --> 23:46.419
So I work six days and I get paid, right?

23:46.800 --> 23:48.043
That's kind of the way it works.

23:48.083 --> 23:52.754
So it's very easy in the system that got to set up for me to sometimes convince myself

23:53.026 --> 23:55.570
that I am the main provider for myself and my family.

23:55.850 --> 24:02.099
And God says, I'm going to institute to Sabbath so to be this weekly reminder to you that it is not your ultimate responsibility.

24:02.139 --> 24:03.281
You are not a slave.

24:03.642 --> 24:05.605
You're not a slave to cultures expectations.

24:05.625 --> 24:07.427
You're not a slave to your family's hopes.

24:07.828 --> 24:11.293
You're not a slave to your medical school's demands.

24:11.634 --> 24:13.697
You're not a slave to your own insecurities.

24:13.717 --> 24:15.880
He says, I'm going to give you a gift.

24:15.900 --> 24:17.102
And I want you to take a day.

24:17.863 --> 24:22.770
And you structured that day around the kind of activities that are going to help you remember the goodness

24:22.946 --> 24:27.172
of God and the grace of God and the love of God.

24:27.212 --> 24:34.702
The Sabbath was a day for me to just stop and open my eyes and remember how good life is.

24:35.763 --> 24:35.944
Right?

24:35.984 --> 24:40.169
It's a state of just slow down and just watch the sunset.

24:41.531 --> 24:41.651
Right?

24:41.671 --> 24:45.036
It's a day to lay in a hammock and read an amazing book.

24:45.416 --> 24:49.522
It's a day to go have a fantastic lunch with friends, unhurried lunch.

24:49.826 --> 24:54.591
where you just enjoy each other and you enjoy the food and the drink and the conversation.

24:54.651 --> 25:05.003
It's a day you just slow down and you shut off or you unplug from whatever you need to shut off and whatever you need unplug from to be reminded that you're not just a machine.

25:05.063 --> 25:18.258
God believes that you have value and when I stop and when you stop and that we remember that we are loved just because we exist

25:19.938 --> 25:24.887
then what we realized so much of our effort is chasing after something we've had all along.

25:26.550 --> 25:27.291
You get that, right?

25:27.391 --> 25:31.058
You were loved just because you exist.

25:32.200 --> 25:38.030
And you got to have that rhythm in your life of stopping and just remembering, yeah, I'm loved just because I exist.

25:38.912 --> 25:42.298
My worth, my value is not directly tied to just the work that I do.

25:42.739 --> 25:44.722
And we all need this rhythm.

25:44.898 --> 25:46.541
Let's make this super practical, right?

25:46.581 --> 25:51.429
I want to get it factored to go way up so that you can't walk out here saying I was totally lost.

25:51.449 --> 25:53.091
I had no clue what that guy was talking about.

25:53.472 --> 25:54.554
So I'm gonna give you some homework.

25:55.415 --> 25:56.417
And I got four questions.

25:56.457 --> 25:57.839
I want you guys to ask yourself.

25:58.500 --> 26:00.223
You can ask it in the context of your marriage.

26:00.283 --> 26:03.528
If you're married, you can involve your whole family in this if you want to.

26:03.768 --> 26:06.833
You can take a picture of these questions because I don't know if they exist anywhere else.

26:06.893 --> 26:08.216
So here's number one.

26:08.256 --> 26:10.619
Number one is can you commit to try for a month?

26:11.240 --> 26:12.242
Just for one month.

26:12.834 --> 26:16.039
reserving one day to rest, revive, and remember.

26:16.439 --> 26:17.801
So one day a week, can you do that?

26:18.102 --> 26:30.340
Can you say, all right, I'm going to do an experiment, and I'm going to try to structure one day a week for a month to have this day that's going to be reserved to rest, revive, and remember.

26:30.781 --> 26:31.802
So that's question number one.

26:32.323 --> 26:35.548
If you answer a note of that question, by the way, you can skip the rest of them, OK?

26:36.930 --> 26:38.452
Number two, which day of the week?

26:39.734 --> 26:42.418
So here's where I don't want us to get really legalistic about this.

26:42.626 --> 26:47.955
So for me, Sunday has never been my Sabbath day, not in my entire adult life.

26:49.157 --> 26:51.261
It's almost anti-Sabbath in some ways, right?

26:51.521 --> 26:52.823
Because it's kind of a work day for me.

26:53.043 --> 26:57.351
And I have Sabbath moments inside of that, but it's not truly my Sabbath.

26:57.751 --> 27:02.459
Because this is a day that I can lean into my gifts and my abilities and not gods.

27:02.499 --> 27:04.082
And I don't want to do that.

27:04.194 --> 27:06.618
For me, I've gotta move that Sabbath to a different day, right?

27:06.938 --> 27:10.103
So I don't know what this looks like for you, but you discuss it.

27:10.243 --> 27:11.264
What day's gonna work best?

27:11.305 --> 27:12.667
What is your Sabbath gonna look like?

27:12.727 --> 27:17.213
Question three, where are the activities that you need to best rest, revive, and remember?

27:17.934 --> 27:20.478
So again, we're all wired differently.

27:21.259 --> 27:29.331
And there's gonna be different things, right, that connects you to God, that remind you of His grace, that remind you of His love, and it's gonna look different for all of us.

27:29.632 --> 27:32.596
Some of you, you just need to take a nap, right?

27:32.876 --> 27:33.938
How many of you are nappers?

27:34.370 --> 27:35.632
I mean, nappers have, oh, that's good.

27:37.494 --> 27:39.376
I was just thinking about the dude that was asleep last week.

27:39.396 --> 27:41.999
He would totally, he wouldn't even have had a chance to raise his hand.

27:42.019 --> 27:43.201
Like, it would have been his moment.

27:44.242 --> 27:47.466
Like, I'm a champion napper, and he totally missed it.

27:48.127 --> 27:50.069
So nap, maybe that's what it is for you.

27:50.089 --> 27:53.053
Sometimes the most spiritual thing you can do is take a nap.

27:53.754 --> 27:54.034
Amen?

27:54.895 --> 27:55.496
Yeah.

27:55.516 --> 27:56.277
All right.

27:56.337 --> 27:56.957
Time on the water.

27:56.997 --> 27:58.740
I'll put that one in there, because that's me.

27:59.060 --> 28:00.722
For some reason, water,

28:00.930 --> 28:04.995
has always been a place and environment where I just easily connect to God in this grace.

28:05.115 --> 28:06.056
I don't know why.

28:06.116 --> 28:11.683
I'm sure if I thought real hard or some experience in my past that taught me that, but that's me.

28:11.964 --> 28:13.525
Some of you, it's worship, it's prayer.

28:13.846 --> 28:15.268
Maybe it's a slow dinner with friends.

28:15.368 --> 28:17.010
Again, don't get legalistic about it.

28:17.050 --> 28:18.131
This is a gift.

28:18.151 --> 28:24.419
Whatever, if it's golf for you, then go play a nice, slow round of golf with some friends, right?

28:25.000 --> 28:30.226
I personally think golf is a fantastic way to ruin a good walk.

28:31.234 --> 28:33.457
So that's not gonna connect me to God.

28:33.557 --> 28:38.965
I might use his name throughout the course, but that's not really connecting me to God.

28:38.985 --> 28:40.847
But you gotta figure that out, brainstorm that, right?

28:40.987 --> 28:43.471
And then number four, what will be some non-negotiables for you?

28:44.252 --> 28:48.217
What are some things that I will do or we will do as a family?

28:48.438 --> 28:49.259
And then what are some things?

28:49.559 --> 28:51.402
We're just not gonna do those things, right?

28:51.702 --> 28:53.284
It disconnects us.

28:53.825 --> 28:57.330
Again, I'm not suggesting this, but maybe for you, it would be social media.

28:57.474 --> 29:01.057
And you just say on Sabbath, whatever day that is, I need to disconnect from that.

29:01.097 --> 29:09.165
Because if there's anything that kind of draws me out of God's presence, and if there's anything that makes me feel like I'm falling further behind, it's social media.

29:09.205 --> 29:20.716
So again, I don't know, again, don't get legalistic about it, but also be smart and use wisdom and be intentional about this and create this day where you can really get out of it what God intended for you.

29:20.996 --> 29:25.401
The biggest thing I want you to hear is a gift, right?

29:25.481 --> 29:26.802
It's this invitation.

29:27.170 --> 29:31.316
And it reminds me of so much of this passage in Matthew chapter 11 where Jesus said this.

29:31.376 --> 29:32.217
He said, come to me.

29:33.559 --> 29:36.062
All of you who are weary and burdened.

29:36.963 --> 29:38.425
Does that describe any of you guys?

29:38.605 --> 29:40.027
All of you who are weary and burdened.

29:40.168 --> 29:42.210
All of you who are overworked.

29:42.230 --> 29:44.714
All of you who are living frenzied lifestyles.

29:46.015 --> 29:51.222
All of you who woke up this morning, you weren't even sure what day of the week it was, because it's just so crazy.

29:51.543 --> 29:52.304
He says, come to me.

29:52.825 --> 29:53.726
And I'm gonna give you a rest.

29:53.766 --> 29:56.850
Take my yoke upon you and learn from me for I am gentle

29:57.058 --> 30:01.443
and humble in heart and you will find rest for your souls.

30:02.204 --> 30:05.147
For my yoke is easy and my burden is light.

30:06.309 --> 30:07.150
Doesn't that sound beautiful?

30:08.331 --> 30:09.272
So I want you to think about it.

30:09.292 --> 30:11.155
Why don't you close your eyes by your head?

30:12.356 --> 30:14.559
Let's just have a little, have a Sabbath moment together.

30:14.579 --> 30:15.119
Can we do that?

30:16.100 --> 30:19.544
Just a moment, just to forget about everything else going on in your life.

30:20.786 --> 30:24.370
And I want you to think about that invitation from Jesus where he says, come to me.

30:25.730 --> 30:27.131
He says, just come to me.

30:30.375 --> 30:32.097
Everybody take a big deep breath.

30:33.979 --> 30:35.280
Hold it for like three seconds.

30:36.782 --> 30:37.442
And exhale.

30:37.482 --> 30:40.446
One more big deep breath.

30:43.088 --> 30:43.809
And exhale.

30:43.829 --> 30:46.672
And Jesus says, come to me.

30:47.934 --> 30:52.178
Listen, all of you that are weary and burdened and frenzied and overwork, I want you to come to me.

30:53.986 --> 30:58.353
And the picture I'm getting in my head right now is I think about my daughter.

30:58.673 --> 31:02.720
She's two and a half and she didn't really know how to hug right now.

31:02.760 --> 31:13.597
And so when I ask her for a hug, instead of coming up to me and wrapping her arms around my neck, she just backs her little body into my body and just kind of falls into me.

31:14.198 --> 31:15.140
And that's a hug for her.

31:15.500 --> 31:17.363
That's what I'm envisioning for you guys right now.

31:18.064 --> 31:19.186
When Jesus says, come to me.

31:20.450 --> 31:27.881
All of you who are weary and burdened and stressed out and overworked and frenzied, it's like just come to me, just kind of lean back into my arms.

31:29.763 --> 31:45.426
And I want you to literally just in this moment feel yourself being embraced by Jesus and feel the warmth of his embrace, the warmth of his love, the warmth of his grace.

31:51.106 --> 31:56.655
So just stay there in that moment and just know that you were loved simply because you exist.

31:58.999 --> 32:05.289
To know in this moment that God could not love you anymore or any less than he does in this very moment.

32:07.894 --> 32:09.676
You're fully known and you're fully loved.

32:12.822 --> 32:15.827
And he knows what you need better than anybody else, including yourself.

32:17.049 --> 32:17.970
And he says, come to me.

32:18.370 --> 32:19.932
All of you who are weary of burden.

32:19.952 --> 32:22.275
He says, I will give you, and here's the key line.

32:22.295 --> 32:25.079
He said, I will give you rest for your souls.

32:27.141 --> 32:28.102
Just think about that for a second.

32:28.183 --> 32:30.145
Rest for your souls.

32:31.226 --> 32:37.975
See, the kind of rest that you need right now in your life is not the kind of rest that's gonna be fixed with a two-hour nap this afternoon.

32:38.035 --> 32:46.546
It's not the kind of rest that's gonna be fixed by a two-week vacation, although you may need that and want that and deserve that.

32:47.586 --> 32:50.790
What Jesus is saying is that you're tired at the soul level.

32:52.291 --> 32:58.358
You're tired in a place that only he alone can breathe life and energy into you.

33:00.861 --> 33:04.045
And all he's trying to do with this Sabbath is help you find a rhythm.

33:05.426 --> 33:08.250
A rhythm that reminds you that he created you.

33:08.270 --> 33:11.433
A rhythm that reminds you that he sustained you.

33:11.453 --> 33:15.698
A rhythm that reminds you of his love and his grace.

33:16.130 --> 33:18.714
and that you're not the general manager of this universe.

33:19.555 --> 33:19.916
He is.

33:21.197 --> 33:22.059
And you can trust them.

33:24.202 --> 33:35.318
And whether or not we're willing to surrender and to lean into his arms and to have these sabbaths determines whether or not we really trust them or whether or not we're just talking a big game.

33:38.122 --> 33:43.410
So God, I pray that you would help us to find a new rhythm, to find a new pattern.

33:45.762 --> 33:56.296
To find a way to institute a Sabbath in our life where we can be reminded that we are loved and we are cared for by a good, good God, that you are fully capable.

33:58.378 --> 34:09.312
I'm not only taking care of our biggest problem, which was our sin problem all by yourself, you're fully capable of sustaining our lives in this world, and we need to trust you.

34:11.796 --> 34:13.618
So help us not to find our identity,

34:14.402 --> 34:17.426
in our work and our frenzy lifestyle, but in you and in you alone.

34:18.867 --> 34:36.048
And so right now, Lord, we just want to take a few minutes where we collectively as a group, corporately as a group, just lean into you, lean into your love, lean into your care, and just be reminded that we are loved simply because we exist.

34:37.710 --> 34:41.394
God, we are so grateful for you and for this rhythm of life.

34:42.018 --> 34:45.584
that you've invited us into, for it's in your holy and your precious name that we pray.

34:46.632 --> 34:46.994
Amen.

